<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-030-115 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 441 313</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  Oct 22 1991 v5 n36 p148(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Coastal Associates Publishing L.P. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Apple releases annual results: revenues up, earnings down. (fiscalyear 1991) (Business Briefs)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Tomlinson, Shawn.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Apple Computer Inc. (Finance).andO;Ticker:    AAPL.andO;Topic:     Fourth QuarterFinancial ReportProfit.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Apple posts results. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Shawn TomlinsonandM;Cupertino, Calif.andP;  -- CEO John Sculley says Apple is on a roll, but thecompany's fiscal-year results, released last week, appear to disagree.andM;Revenues rose 14 percent for 1991, but net income dropped 18 percent duringthe same period.andP;  The company blamed the decline in income mainly on acontinuing decline in gross margins.andM;Apple's revenues for fiscal 1991, which ended Sept.andP;  27, increased to $6.3billion compared with $5.5 billion in 1990.andP;  Income for the year dropped to$309.8 million or $2.58 per share, down from $474.9 million or $3.77 pershare in 1990.andP;  The income-per-share reflects $1.16 per share that Apple setaside last quarter for restructuring costs.andM;Revenues for the fourth quarter were $1.5 billion, up 11 percent from thesame quarter last year.andP;  Income for the fourth quarter fell 18 percent to$81.2 million, or 67 cents per share.andM;Despite the drops, analysts said they were not concerned.andP;  &quot;It was a verygood quarter,&quot; said Peter Rogers, computer analyst for Robertson, Stephens andamp;Co. in San Francisco.andP;  &quot;andlsqb;Appleandrsqb; has a number of new products that couldmaintain growth between 10 and 20 percent through 1992.andP;  We also have seenthe company reduce spending levels, and gross margins appear to be bottomingout.&quot;andM;Margins for the fourth quarter fell slightly to 43.4 percent from 45.8percent the previous quarter, Rogers said.andM;Apple's net income for the year included a one-time charge of $224 million or$138.9 million after tax for restructuring and other expenses, includinglegal expenses, such as its settlement of the lawsuit with the Beatles overthe use of the name Apple (see MacWEEK, Oct.andP;  15).andP;  The charges resulted in a$53.1 million loss in the third quarter.andM;Apple said it shipped 60 percent more units in 1991 than it did last year.andO;Profits fell due to a shift in the product line toward lower-cost,lower-margin models.andM;&quot;We are within a quarter or two of Apple showing some very positive earningsgains,&quot; Rogers said.andP;  &quot;1991 was a year of transition.&quot;andO;</TEXT></DOC>